  "opinion": "As a plumber in Washington DC with a background that’s more hands-on than academic, I’ve seen how science gets framed in ways that feel disconnected from everyday life. The gender gap in science isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to see themselves in the stories we tell. I’ve volunteered at local science fairs, and I’ve noticed how many kids, especially girls, get turned off early because the examples of scientists they see are all men—people who wear lab coats and talk about complex equations, not the practical problem-solving that happens in a plumbing job. It’s not that girls can’t handle science; it’s that the narrative doesn’t reflect the kinds of work that matter to them. Should we address it? Absolutely. But not with another lecture about equality—it’s about making science feel relevant. For instance, when I explain how pipe systems work, I use real-world examples that kids can relate to, like fixing leaks in their homes or designing water systems for their communities. That’s the kind of approach we need: science that’s grounded in the lives people actually live. My creative side makes me think outside the box—maybe we could create workshops where kids build simple machines together, without a single person being labeled as the 'expert' or 'the one who knows.' This isn’t about changing the rules of science; it’s about changing how we share it so everyone feels they belong. After all, if science feels like it’s out of reach, then no one will ever see themselves in it.",
